  year     = {2014},
  volume   = {795},
  number   = {2},
  pages    = {145},
  abstract = {We present Keck-I MOSFIRE near-infrared spectroscopy for a sample of 13 compact star-forming galaxies (SFGs) at redshift 2 ≤ z ≤ 2.5 with star formation rates of SFR ~ 100 M ☉ yr –1 and masses of log( M / M ☉ ) ~10.8. Their high integrated gas velocity dispersions of σ int ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/795/2/145/apj502362ieqn1.gif] {$=230^{+40}_{-30}$} km s –1 , as measured from emission lines of Hα and [O III ], and the resultant M ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/icons/Entities/sstarf.gif] {sstarf} -σ int relation and M ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/icons/Entities/sstarf.gif] {sstarf} - M dyn all match well to those of compact quiescent galaxies at z ~ 2, as measured from stellar absorption lines. Since log( M ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/icons/Entities/sstarf.gif] {sstarf} / M dyn ) =–0.06 ± 0.2 dex, these compact SFGs appear to be dynamically relaxed and evolved, i.e., depleted in gas and dark matter (<13 ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/795/2/145/apj502362ieqn2.gif] {$^{+17}_{-13}$} %), and present larger σ int than their non-compact SFG counterparts at the same epoch. Without infusion of external gas, depletion timescales are short, less than ~300 Myr. This discovery adds another link to our new dynamical chain of evidence that compact SFGs at z ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/icons/Entities/gsim.gif] {gsim} 2 are already losing gas to become the immediate progenitors of compact quiescent galaxies by z ~ 2.},
  file     = {:mcg/Barro2014a.pdf:PDF},
