  number   = {2},
  pages    = {133},
  abstract = {We report the source size distribution, as measured by ALMA millimetric continuum imaging, of a sample of 13 AzTEC-selected submillimeter galaxies (SMGs) at ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn3.gif] {${z}_{\mathrm{phot}}\sim 3$} –6. Their infrared luminosities and star formation rates (SFRs) are ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn4.gif] {${L}_{\mathrm{IR}}\sim \;$} 2– ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn5.gif] {$6\times {10}^{12}$} ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn6.gif] {${L}_{\odot }$} and ∼200–600 ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn7.gif] {${M}_{\odot }$} yr −1 , respectively. The sizes of these SMGs range from 0.″10 to 0.″38, with a median of 0.″20 ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn8.gif] {${}_{-0\buildrel{\prime\prime}\over{.} 05}^{+0\buildrel{\prime\prime}\over{.} 03}$} (FWHM), corresponding to a median circularized effective radius ( ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn9.gif] {${R}_{{\rm{c}},{\rm{e}}}$} ) of ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn10.gif] {${0.67}_{-0.14}^{+0.13}$} kpc, comparable to the typical size of the stellar component measured in compact quiescent galaxies at ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn11.gif] {$z\sim 2$} (cQGs)— ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn12.gif] {${R}_{{\rm{e}}}\sim 1$} kpc. The median surface SFR density of our SMGs is ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn13.gif] {${100}_{-26}^{+42}$} ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn14.gif] {${M}_{\odot }$} yr −1 kpc −2 , comparable to that seen in local merger-driven (U)LIRGs rather than in extended disk galaxies at low and high redshifts. The discovery of compact starbursts in ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn15.gif] {$z\gtrsim 3$} SMGs strongly supports a massive galaxy formation scenario wherein ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn16.gif] {$z\sim 3$} –6 SMGs evolve into the compact stellar components of ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn17.gif] {$z\sim 2$} cQGs. These cQGs are then thought to evolve into the most massive ellipticals in the local universe, mostly via dry mergers. Our results thus suggest that ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/0004-637X/810/2/133/apj518788ieqn18.gif] {$z\gtrsim 3$} SMGs are the likely progenitors of massive local ellipticals, via cQGs, meaning that we can now trace the evolutionary path of the most massive galaxies over a period encompassing ∼90% of the age of the universe.},
  groups   = {high-z/CG, highz/CG},
  url      = {http://stacks.iop.org/0004-637X/810/i=2/a=133},
}

